  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Concept emerged from efforts to combat organized crime in the early 20th century\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities like bootlegging and gambling\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970)\n- First major U.S. legislation targeting money laundering\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Development\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global problem\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Developed comprehensive international standards for combating financial crimes\n\n4. Key Legislation\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Comprehensive Crime Control Act (1984)\n- Anti-Drug Abuse Act (1986)\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Significantly expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Enhanced financial monitoring and reporting requirements\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Global Regulatory Framework\n- Expanded international cooperation\n- More stringent Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency and digital financial transactions\n\nThis progression reflects increasing complexity and sophistication in addressing financial crimes.",
